Economic Interdependence and Conflict

Thomas Chadefaux

PO 4700: Contemporary International Relations

Today’s puzzle

Country A tells country B that it will be attacked at noon on one weekday in the following week.

“The bombing will come as a surprise”, says A.

People in country B rejoice.

Today’s Lecture

Notes

Four versions of the argument.

  • Some argue that economic interdependence promotes peace.
  • Others say that it depends on the type of relationship or the type of good that is traded. Trade may increase conflict
  • Yet others say that economic interdependence promotes conflict
  • Finally, argument that trade has no net effect on conflict

1 Trade Promotes Peace

1.1 Three versions of the liberal proposition

  • Welfare loss if trading stops
  • Contact hypothesis
  • Business interests

1.1 Notes:

  1. Perhaps the argument receiving the most attention suggests that states are deterred from initiating conflict against a trading partner for fear of losing the welfare gains associated with the trading relationship. The diminution of trade or barriers to trade that accompany conflict lead to welfare losses.

  2. Contact hypothesis: Idea that commerce civilizes, polishes, and pacifies states and their citizens. In 1749, Monstesquieu wrote “Commerce […] polishes and softens […] barbaric ways as we can see every day (quoted in Hirschman 1982, 1464).”Commerce cures destructive prejudices“. Greater contacts, according to this view, produce greater understanding and more peaceful unions. In addition, increased contact necessitates the creation of mechanisms, such as laws, to resolve conflicts of interest that might arise.

  3. Business interests will mobilize their opposition to war in the interest of maintaining trade ties (economic profits). Some liberals add that this is particularly true in democratic societies, where public opinion has a greater impact on policymakers (Domke 1988; Ray 1995). But objection to this argument: many instances in which businesses profit from war or in which economic interests prefer conflict to peace (Barbieri and Levy 1999).

1.2 But Is Conflict Really Costly in Terms of Trade?

1.2 Notes

There is a long history of trading with the enemy, so that war does not necessarily decrease trade \(\rightarrow\) low opportunity cost

Empirically, Barbieri and Levy (1999) find that in most cases, war has no statistically significant effect on dyadic trade. This finding is questionable (see Anderton, Charles H., and John R. Carter. “The impact of war on trade: An interrupted times-series study.” Journal of Peace Research 38.4 (2001): 445-457. ], but raises the question sufficiently.

Another important question is how quickly trade resumes after the war

2 It Depends

2.1 Dependency Theory

Trade as a means of influence

  • Trade is unfavourable to developing nations
  • Wealthy nations actively perpetuate a state of dependence, possibly through military means
  • Powerful states more likely to intervene militarily in weaker, economically dependent states (Wallensteen 1973)

2.1 Notes:

Short Intro video to dependency theory

  • Emerged 1960s-70s
  • Idea: some countries are not developing because the international system is preventing them
  • Dependence arises from a state’s inability to spread its imports and exports equally over a large number of countries This is in contrast to liberals, for whom the more dependent state, such as a developing nation, generally enjoys greater economic benefits from an opportunity to trade with a large state than the large state derives from the relationship
  • Gains from trade enjoyed exclusively by developed states. Poor nations provide natural resources, cheap labour, a destination for obsolete technology, and markets for developed nations, without which the latter could not have the standard of living they enjoy.
  • Trade retards the development of developing states.
  • Trade exacerbates inequality
  • Wallensteen (1973): powerful states are more likely than minor powers to intervene militarily with underdogs that are dependent upon them economically. (e.g., Latin American states)
  • Wealthy nations actively perpetuate a state of dependence by various means. This influence may be multifaceted, involving economics, media control, politics, banking and finance, education, culture, and sport.

2.2 Relative Gains

  • Unequal gains from trade
    • Dissatisfaction with the distribution
    • Concern over shifts in power
  • Security externalities
    • Increased productive efficiency \(\rightarrow\) military productivity
    • Transfers of technology

2.2 Notes:

Neorealists: even when absolute gains exist, concerns about relative gains may dominate leaders’ decisions (Baldwin 1993; Grieco 1990; Mastanduno 1993; Powell 1991; Snidal 1991, 1993). Even when states are thought to benefit absolutely from trade, one state might consider its partner’s disproportionate gain to be a loss to itself in terms of relative power. E.g., US-China.

Gowa (1994) thus argues that states choose to trade with allies in order to avoid granting the gain from trade to adversaries, which results in security externalities. The main problem is that trade may increase the opponent’s productive efficiency and allow it to redirect resources toward military resources.

2.3 Does Conquest Pay?

  • Trade and conquest as alternative means of obtaining goods
  • Trade only when conquest is not profitable \(\rightarrow\) when is conquest profitable?

2.3 Notes

We can imagine instances in which the acquisition of resources through conflict remains a viable and at times more desirable option than trade.

The question, then, is: when is conquest profitable?

  • Traditional argument: only when resources are easily monopolised (e.g., raw material)
  • But industrialised societies can be exploited too. Peter Liberman argues that invaders can exploit industrial societies for short periods of time and can maintain control and economic performance over the long term. This is because modern societies are uniquely vulnerable to coercion and repression. Liberman’s argument is supported by several historical case studies:
    • Belgium and Luxembourg in WWI
    • Most of Europe in WWII
    • France’s seizure of the Ruhr in 1923-24
    • Japanese empire 1910-45
    • Soviet control of Eastern Europe, 1945-89

2.4 What Trade?

The answer might depend on the type of trade

  • Elasticity
    • inelastic \(\rightarrow\) increased vulnerability \(\rightarrow\) fewer conflicts
    • inelastic \(\rightarrow\) increased vulnerability \(\rightarrow\) take military action to reduce vulnerability
  • Lootability

2.4 Notes:

Elasticity: Goods that are more difficult and thus more costly to substitute should have a stronger pacifying effect (see Polachek and McDonald (1992) for empirical evidence). But counterargument: trade also increases dependence \(\rightarrow\) take military action to reduce econ vulnerability (e.g., raw material).

Unfortunately, it is difficult to measure the importance of different types of trade for a country, particularly on a broad historical and temporal domain.

See also Dorussen, JCR 2006: “The central hypotheses are tested using dyadic United Nations trade data disaggregated at industry level from 1970 to 1997. The main findings are that trade generally reduces the likelihood of conflict, the relationship is weaker for commodities that are more easily appropriable by force, and the relationship is generally stronger for manufactured goods with the notable exceptions of chemical and metal industries and the high-technology sector.”

3 Trade Breeds Conflict

3.1 Trade itself is not always peaceful

  • Trade Wars
    • E.g., Anglo-Irish trade war, 1932-38
  • Trade as an instrument of coercion
    • Econ sanctions as a form of conflict
  • Trade increases uncertainty about costs of war. Uncertainty breeds conflict
    • But trade reduce probability that disputes escalate to conflict

3.1 Notes:

Stein: The historical record is replete with trade wars (Conybeare 1987), and these arise only among countries with extensive commercial ties that are, typically, politically close. The growth of trade generates trade frictions and disputes. Trade has, moreover, been used as an instrument of coercion. Countries with extensive economic links have been prepared to cut such ties to compel a change in others’ policies. But econ sanctions are a form of conflict, and they presuppose some interdependence.

However, trade reduces the chance that disputes escalate to conflict because it provides additional ways of signalling resolve and commitment. In that sense, econ sanctions are an intermediate step between mere diplomacy and military measures. In conflicts of interest in which there are no economic links, states have little choice between mere diplomacy and military steps.

Now you may note that sanctions often don’t work. Indeed, they often don’t work to obtain concessions (mainly because of a selection effect). But they may still be a deterrent and prevent escalation. They also deter THIRD parties.

Finally, an empirical relationship between trade and conflict may simply capture the uncertainty in the relationship. Higher levels of trade are associated with greater certainty in the relationship between states, and lower levels of trade are associated with greater uncertainty.

3.2 Marxist Approaches

  • Trade siphons off resources from poor countries
  • Lenin: Competition over markets and resources as an inherent feature of capitalism
  • Difference with dependency theorists: collusion vs clash between great powers

3.2 Notes:

Neo-Marxists reject the assumption that trade provides net benefits to all states. Trade and economic dependence benefit the powerful, but result in political and economic costs for the powerless.

Idea: trade between developed and developing nations siphons off resources from the poor to the rich state (see Galtung 1971).

Competition over markets and resources as an inherent feature of capitalism (Baran 1957; Sweezy 1942). This competition can easily result in violent conflict between major powers, as well as the domination of less powerful states. Lateral pressure theory also envisions conflict corresponding with shortages of resources and markets (Choucri and North 1975, 1989). The result can be trade wars, investment wars, or even hegemonic wars

Difference between Marxist-Leninist and Dependency theory (see Rosecrance (1986)): Dependency theories assume a degree of collusion among developed capitalist states, with conflict arising in relations between unequal partners. Lenin, however, argues that the highest stage of capitalist development’s imperialism leads to conflict among the most advanced capitalist nations as they vie for control over new markets, sources of raw materials, and scarce resources.

4 Insignificant Effect on Conflict

4.1 Realists

Trade is secondary to security \(\rightarrow\) not a sufficient deterrent

4.1 Notes:

“For realists, economic considerations remain subordinate to military concerns in realist assessments of leaders’ decisions to engage in conflict. According to realist logic, trade will not create a sufficient deterrent to conflict. This does not mean that trade ties are unimportant for realists. Trade is recognized as a tool of influence. Trading relationships with states that provide strategic com- modities are also valued. However, when faced with questions about whether to engage in conflict, leaders do not necessarily evaluate the potential harm that might be caused to a trading relationship” (Barbieri 2009)

4.2 The Bargaining Approach

  • Expected loss of trade is an added cost… But the other side should raise its demand as a result \(\rightarrow\) unclear effect

  • Trade creates more uncertainty \(\rightarrow\) increased probability of war … But also more opportunities for signalling

4.2 Notes:

Morrow (1999): The loss of trade as a consequence of war produces an added cost and so should make a state more willing to make concessions to avoid war. At the same time, though, the other side should raise its demand as a result, because it knows that the first state is more willing to make concessions \(\rightarrow\) the relationship between trade and war is therefore indeterminate.

Any factor that disadvantages one party in a contest generally provides added leverage to opponents.

So changes in the level of costs should have little effect on the probability of disputes because factors that alter the relative bargaining power of competitors are also likely to result in changes in the settlements that ensue from bargaining, rather than leading to changes in the frequency of bargaining failures.

However, trade can create more uncertainty about how costly the war is, and in that sense increase the proba of war.

On the other hand, trade provides more opportunities for signalling (e.g., sanctions, etc.)

4.3 The Endogeneity of Trade

4.3 Notes:

  • Peace \(\rightarrow\) trade, or the opposite?
  • Trade presupposes peace. Government will redirect trade to nations at peace
  • Traders and foreign investors prefer stability and avoid conflict -> conflict reduces trade
  • Trade tends to take place within alliances

Today’s lecture: summary

  1. Trade promotes peace:
    • Welfare loss
    • Contact hypothesis
    • Business interests
  2. It depends:
    • Conflict may not affect trade
    • Asymmetric trade
    • Relative gains
    • Trade vs conquest
    • Different goods, different effects
  3. Trade breeds conflict
    • Trade wars
    • Marxism: Capitalism -> Competition over resources
    • Third parties
  4. Insignificant effect
    • Security primes trade
    • More costs -> more demands
    • Trade \(\rightarrow\) peace, peace \(\rightarrow\) trade, or alliances \(\rightarrow\) trade \(\rightarrow\) peace?

Answer to Today’s Puzzle

“Unexpected hanging paradox”

If no bombing on Saturday night, then there can be no bombing on Sunday, as this would not be a surprise. So Sunday is out. But by the same reasoning, Saturday is out, etc.
